HEADWORD: Sthenic
<hw>Sthen"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ strength:
cf. F. <ets>sth⟦eacute⟧nique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld>
<def>Strong; active; -- said especially of morbid states attended with
excessive action of the heart and blood vessels, and characterized by
strength and activity of the muscular and nervous system; <as>as, a
<ex>sthenic</ex> fever</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sthenic theory</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Stimulism</er>
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

